<!doctype html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><meta name="description" content="Project RAY research on external memory, experience-based knowledge accumulation, and future humanoid AI."><meta name="theme-color" content="#050914"><meta property="og:title" content="Project RAY | Zhansaya AI Portfolio"><meta property="og:description" content="Project RAY research on external memory, experience-based knowledge accumulation, and future humanoid AI."><meta property="og:type" content="website"><meta property="og:url" content="https://jans-saya.github.io/"><link rel="icon" href="assets/images/ui/logo.svg"><link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com"><link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin><link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600;700&family=Space+Grotesk:wght@500;600;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet"><link rel="stylesheet" href="assets/css/site.css"><title>Project RAY | Zhansaya AI Portfolio</title></head><body class="project-page ray-page"><canvas id="network" aria-hidden="true"></canvas><div class="noise" aria-hidden="true"></div><header class="site-header"><div class="nav-shell"><a class="brand" href="index.html"><img src="assets/images/ui/logo.svg" alt=""/><span>ZHANSAYA / AI PORTFOLIO</span></a><button class="menu-toggle" aria-label="Toggle navigation" aria-expanded="false"><span></span><span></span></button><nav class="main-nav" aria-label="Main navigation"><a href="index.html">Home</a><div class="nav-group"><button class="nav-drop" aria-expanded="false">Research <span>⌄</span></button><div class="dropdown"><a href="ray.html"><b>Project RAY</b><small>External memory and humanoid AI</small></a><a href="ray.html#benchmark"><b>Memory Benchmark</b><small>Internal vs external knowledge</small></a><a href="ray.html#papers"><b>Reports</b><small>Methods, results, and future work</small></a></div></div><div class="nav-group"><button class="nav-drop" aria-expanded="false">Engineering <span>⌄</span></button><div class="dropdown"><a href="sign-language.html"><b>Sign Language Translator</b><small>Computer vision and accessibility</small></a><a href="glove.html"><b>Gesture Smart Glove</b><small>Wearable input prototype</small></a><a href="doit.html"><b>DOIT</b><small>AI productivity web app</small></a></div></div><a href="index.html#credentials">Credentials</a><a href="resume.html">Resume</a><a class="nav-cta" href="index.html#contact">Contact</a></nav></div></header><main><section class="project-hero"><div class="project-hero-copy reveal"><p class="kicker">PROJECT 01 · NLP / MEMORY / ROBOTICS</p><h1>Project <em>RAY</em></h1><p class="lede">I am developing Project RAY to study whether an AI agent can use stored interactions as external memory. The physical humanoid is not complete; the current work covers the research design, memory benchmark, and system architecture.</p><div class="status-row"><span class="status active">BENCHMARK COMPLETE</span><span class="status">HARDWARE IN DEVELOPMENT</span><span class="status">2026</span></div><div class="actions"><a class="btn primary" href="#benchmark">Read findings</a><a class="btn ghost" href="#papers">Open reports</a><a class="btn ghost" href="https://github.com/jans-saya/RAY-benchmark" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Code ↗</a></div></div><div class="project-hero-media reveal delay"><img src="assets/images/ui/ray-system.svg" alt="Project RAY memory architecture concept"><div class="media-note">CONCEPT ARCHITECTURE · NOT A CLAIM OF COMPLETED HARDWARE</div></div></section><section class="section"><div class="section-label reveal"><span>01</span><p>RESEARCH QUESTION</p></div><div class="split-intro"><h2 class="reveal">How strongly can external memory influence a frozen language model when it conflicts with pretrained knowledge?</h2><div class="reveal delay"><p>I want RAY to learn from speech, camera input, and repeated interaction. The main problem is that a pretrained language model already contains extensive internal knowledge, so it can ignore or combine a retrieved memory with what it already knows.</p><p>Before building the humanoid hardware, I isolated the conflict between internal model knowledge and external memory in a controlled benchmark.</p></div></div><div class="quote-panel reveal"><blockquote>“If the model always answers from its pretrained knowledge, adding memory on top does not produce real experience-based accumulation.”</blockquote><span>Benchmark objective</span></div></section><section class="section process-section"><div class="section-label reveal"><span>02</span><p>PLANNED SYSTEM</p></div><div class="flow-diagram reveal"><div class="flow-node"><b>01</b><strong>Perceive</strong><span>Speech + camera input</span></div><i>→</i><div class="flow-node"><b>02</b><strong>Store</strong><span>Interaction memories</span></div><i>→</i><div class="flow-node"><b>03</b><strong>Retrieve</strong><span>Relevant past context</span></div><i>→</i><div class="flow-node"><b>04</b><strong>Generate</strong><span>Local LLM response</span></div><i>→</i><div class="flow-node"><b>05</b><strong>Act</strong><span>Speech + movement</span></div></div><div class="note-grid"><article class="note-card reveal"><span>FIRST IMPLEMENTATION</span><h3>RAG + Qwen + FAISS</h3><p>I first used Qwen2.5-1.5B, FAISS, and a synthetic persona dataset. Retrieval worked, but the dataset gave RAY thousands of conversations that it had not experienced.</p></article><article class="note-card reveal delay"><span>WHY I CHANGED THE DESIGN</span><h3>Remove synthetic personal memories</h3><p>I removed the preloaded persona conversations because they contradicted the project goal. The revised design starts without fictional experiences and adds memories only from actual interaction.</p></article><article class="note-card reveal"><span>RESEARCH QUESTION</span><h3>Behavior without a fixed persona prompt</h3><p>I want to test whether behavior can change through memory and interaction instead of being fixed in a system prompt.</p></article></div></section><section class="section benchmark" id="benchmark"><div class="section-label reveal"><span>03</span><p>EXTERNAL MEMORY BENCHMARK</p></div><div class="section-title-row"><h2 class="reveal">Benchmark method and results.</h2><p class="reveal delay">I used deliberately false memory statements as controlled source signals. This made it easier to identify whether an answer followed the supplied memory or the model’s pretrained knowledge.</p></div><div class="benchmark-grid"><div class="benchmark-summary reveal"><div class="big-stat"><strong>30</strong><span>evaluated test cases</span></div><p>Each question was answered twice: once without memory and once with an external memory statement added as context.</p><ul class="clean-list"><li><b>Generator:</b> Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct</li><li><b>Semantic evaluator:</b> cross-encoder/nli-MiniLM2-L6-H768</li><li><b>Similarity:</b> sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2</li><li><b>Dataset:</b> 100 deliberately false statements; 30 used in final run</li></ul></div><div class="result-panel reveal delay"><div class="result-row"><span>External memory dominated</span><div><i style="--w:100%"></i></div><b>14</b></div><div class="result-row"><span>Partial external influence</span><div><i style="--w:36%"></i></div><b>5</b></div><div class="result-row"><span>Internal knowledge dominated</span><div><i style="--w:14%"></i></div><b>2</b></div><div class="result-row"><span>Mixed or unclear</span><div><i style="--w:64%"></i></div><b>9</b></div><div class="result-highlight"><strong>27 / 30</strong><span>cases showed higher external-memory influence than the no-memory baseline.</span></div></div></div><div class="metric-cards"><article class="metric-card reveal"><span>AVG INTERNAL INFLUENCE</span><strong>0.022</strong></article><article class="metric-card reveal delay"><span>AVG EXTERNAL INFLUENCE</span><strong>0.485</strong></article><article class="metric-card reveal"><span>AVG MEMORY GAIN</span><strong>0.464</strong></article></div><div class="formula-card reveal"><div><span>EXTERNAL MEMORY INFLUENCE</span><code>0.55 × NLI score + 0.45 × keyword evidence</code></div><div><span>MEMORY GAIN</span><code>external influence − internal influence</code></div></div></section><section class="section"><div class="section-label reveal"><span>04</span><p>RESULTS AND LIMITATIONS</p></div><div class="insight-grid"><article class="insight reveal"><span>RESULT</span><h3>External memory influenced many answers.</h3><p>The same question often produced a different answer after the external memory statement was added.</p></article><article class="insight reveal delay"><span>LIMITATION</span><h3>Pretrained knowledge remained active.</h3><p>Two cases were still dominated by internal knowledge, and nine were mixed or unclear. The benchmark shows context influence, not removal of pretrained knowledge.</p></article><article class="insight reveal"><span>NEXT BENCHMARK</span><h3>Evaluate more cases and add retrieval testing.</h3><p>I plan to evaluate all 100 statements, add more concepts, compare models and prompts, and test FAISS retrieval failures separately.</p></article><article class="insight reveal delay"><span>LONG-TERM DEVELOPMENT</span><h3>Short-term and long-term memory.</h3><p>I plan to add short-term and long-term memory, repeated-experience reinforcement, correction handling, and importance-aware retrieval.</p></article></div></section><section class="section papers" id="papers"><div class="section-label reveal"><span>05</span><p>REPORTS</p></div><div class="documents"><details class="document reveal" open><summary><div><span>BENCHMARK REPORT · 7 PAGES</span><h3>Testing External Memory Influence in a Humanoid AI Agent</h3></div><b>⌄</b></summary><div class="document-body"><p>Full methodology, verdict thresholds, score design, example outputs, graph, discussion, limitations, and future work.</p><a class="btn primary" href="documents/ray-external-memory-benchmark.pdf">Open PDF ↗</a></div></details><details class="document reveal"><summary><div><span>RESEARCH VISION · 3 PAGES</span><h3>Testing Experience-Based Knowledge Accumulation</h3></div><b>⌄</b></summary><div class="document-body"><p>The wider humanoid concept, the first RAG implementation, the change in memory design, and research questions about vocabulary, memory selection, reinforcement, and related concepts.</p><a class="btn primary" href="documents/ray-project-vision.pdf">Open PDF ↗</a></div></details></div></section><section class="section next-project"><div class="next-card"><span>NEXT PROJECT</span><h2>Sign Language Translator</h2><p>I built a computer vision prototype after researching accessibility needs and interviewing potential users.</p><a class="btn primary" href="sign-language.html">Continue →</a></div></section></main><footer class="site-footer"><div><a class="brand footer-brand" href="index.html"><img src="assets/images/ui/logo.svg" alt=""/><span>ZHANSAYA / AI PORTFOLIO</span></a><p>Artificial Intelligence major at Pusan National University.<br/>NLP · Computer Vision · Robotics · Human–Computer Interaction</p></div><div class="footer-links"><a href="mailto:zhansaya.k29.12.04@gmail.com">Email</a><a href="tel:+821065930336">+82 10-6593-0336</a><a href="https://github.com/jans-saya" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">GitHub ↗</a></div><div class="footer-bottom"><span>© <span data-year></span> Zhansaya Kyrgyzmolda</span><span>Built and maintained by Zhansaya Kyrgyzmolda.</span></div></footer><div class="lightbox" aria-hidden="true" role="dialog" aria-modal="true"><button class="lightbox-close" aria-label="Close image">×</button><button class="lightbox-prev" aria-label="Previous image">←</button><figure><img alt=""><figcaption></figcaption></figure><button class="lightbox-next" aria-label="Next image">→</button></div><script src="assets/js/site.js"></script></body></html>